3 Loading Microarray data

Affymetrix arrays were done at NIEHS genomic core and analyzed by Jianying Li. Details were documented at analysis.

Main steps are * Normalized by RMA * Filtered by pvac for non-informative probes * ANOVA model * Followed by Tukeyâs contrast for comparison of interest * DEGs were extracted based on p-value and folde change

#Comparing count-based (Jianying) vs.Â rpkm (Ozzy)

We have tried count-based analysis (DESeq, edgeR, baySeq and TSPM), when we

  • Got count from the alignment .bam files
  • Fitted different models (depeneds on which package we used)
  • Getting DEGs based on two-group comparison: etc. day3 vs.Â day0
  • Each model rendered a list of DEG based on p-value or FDR and fold change

##Comparison based on biological significance (fold change)

# Since there was ONLY logFC produced by count-based analysis
# It is needed to convert it backt o fold change

covert.to.foldchange <- function (log2FC)
{
  FC.return <- c()
  for (i in 1:length(log2FC))
  {
    if (is.na(log2FC[i]) | is.infinite (log2FC[i]))
    {
      FC.return[i] <- "NA"
    }else if (log2FC[i] >=0)
      {
       FC.return[i] <- log2FC[i]**2
    }else{
      FC.return[i] <- -(1/(2**log2FC[i]))
    }
  } 
  return (as.numeric(FC.return))
}

##Comparison based on biological significance (fold change)

# Since there was ONLY logFC produced by count-based analysis
# It is needed to convert it backt o fold change

covert.to.foldchange <- function (log2FC)
{
  FC.return <- c()
  for (i in 1:length(log2FC))
  {
    if (is.na(log2FC[i]) | is.infinite (log2FC[i]))
    {
      FC.return[i] <- "NA"
    }else if (log2FC[i] >=0)
      {
       FC.return[i] <- log2FC[i]**2
    }else{
      FC.return[i] <- -(1/(2**log2FC[i]))
    }
  } 
  return (as.numeric(FC.return))
}

5 Conclusion

There were minimum overlap between RNAseq and microarray experiment. Alternatively, the scientists (Janine) proposed to see whether the pathway or downstream pathway would have more overlap.
